      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen reading a text—or even a mathematical formula—we are often tempted to assume immediately that we understand it and, consequently, that it is correct.\n\nThere are several reasons that lead us to this conclusion. However, in this introduction we will highlight one of them: the need for security, the comfort of being right, as opposed to the insecurity and fears that have accompanied us since our earliest moments of life (<htcite0>).\n\nThis fact leads us to a reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e7e25a56-56ae-4e3c-8b00-a55a32a0f945",
                     "text": "Freud, Sigmund",
                     "page": "pp. 244, footnotes",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1913",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Security</b><br /><br />Do you feel uncomfortable when you don’t have answers?<br /><br />Do you feel uncomfortable with your mistakes?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "To help us in this reflection, we will work in parallel with the sacred book of the Maya people, the *Popol-Vuh* (<htcite0>; <htcite1>), originating from Mesoamerica (*Abya Yala*), and with the relationship between force and acceleration proposed by Isaac Newton (<htcite2>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 2,
                     "uuid": "8fcee36c-411a-4fc8-8217-b9a07a34d3da",
                     "text": "Popol Vuh, Español",
                     "page": "pp. 39",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2021",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 2,
                     "uuid": "74bdb72d-1770-4694-8f8e-71e680f1d49c",
                     "text": "Popol Vuh, English",
                     "page": "Ch. 3, pp. 8",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1954",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9f86c1c9-1fd7-4d22-95f6-a1b5ed13b1ee",
                     "text": "Newton, Isaac",
                     "page": "pp. 5",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1686",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_popolvuh",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Indigenous Writing\n\nIn the region known today as Mesoamerica (*Abya Yala*) (<htcite0>), a hieroglyphic writing system was developed. These texts were inscribed on various media, such as stelae found in Copán, Honduras.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2d720f02-051c-4469-b425-7d020f2c2f9b",
                     "text": "Creamer, W.",
                     "page": "pp. 37 - 55",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1987",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgCopanStelaA\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCopanStelaA', '0%')\" src=\"images/Copan/StelaACopan.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width:30%\"/><b>Figure 4</b>: Stela A at the Copán Archaeological Museum, featuring inscriptions referencing Copán, Tikal, Calakmul, and Palenque in sequence (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641'); return false;\">Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia, <htdate0></a>). Photo taken on <htdate1> during site visit.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "7",
                     "day": "30"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "This image displays a hieroglyphic text arranged in two columns.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In addition to the stelae, Indigenous peoples such as the Maya also wrote texts in the form of codices. Unfortunately, many of these codices were burned by Diego de Landa, who was unable to understand them (<htcite0>).\n\nThe destruction caused by Landa was not mirrored among all clergy. This context led, between <htdate0> and <htdate1>, to the compilation of ancient beliefs in what we now know as the **Popol Vuh** (<htcite1>). This event had consequences that went beyond the simple preservation of traditions. According to studies by Miguel R. Dourado, some texts do not reflect the original Mayan beliefs exactly, as they show Christian influences (<htcite2>).\n\n#### Popol Vuh\n\nThe sacred book of the Kʼicheʼ Maya expresses their understanding of cosmology and creation before the arrival of Christianity with the colonizers (<htcite3>).\n\nOriginally, the *Popol Vuh* possibly composed of a single poem. When translated into European languages, it was divided into four distinct parts that narrate the attempts to create humankind (<htcite4>).\n\nNext, we will examine a narrative found in the *Popol Vuh*. But first, another reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b7fa522f-cdc0-47e1-b0a5-049a2bb463db",
                     "text": "Timmer, David E.",
                     "page": "pp. 479-480",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "3",
                        "day": "21"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "85cb27e2-5854-456d-9a0a-2123fa5c0975",
                     "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                     "page": "Popol Vuh",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "3",
                        "day": "21"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0fe64269-28a5-4f86-a0a2-aaf78619183f",
                     "text": "Dourado, Miguel R.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "85cb27e2-5854-456d-9a0a-2123fa5c0975",
                     "text": "Mark, J. J.",
                     "page": "Popol Vuh",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
