            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Contradictions</b><br /><br />When you encounter an idea that contradicts your own, do you immediately classify it as wrong?<br /><br />Or do you stop, think, and study that opposing idea?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Inorganic Matter and Life\n\nToday, when we speak of living beings, we often limit ourselves to plants and animals—but it has not always been this way. Many ancient peoples believed in “lightning stones,” to which they attributed great importance in relation to life (<htcite0>).\n\nWhen reading the *Popol Vuh*, we also find that, according to the narratives, in ancient times “all spoke: grinding stones” (<htcite1>; <htcite2>).\n\nAt first glance, this relationship between stones, texts, and beliefs might lead us to conclude that such ideas are mistaken. On the other hand, it may also show that certain perspectives only consider two extremes, leading to polarized thinking (<htcite3>)",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "56169de2-3737-4ca2-a857-ffc29bf9fb35",
                     "text": "Garcia Castro, Juan Antonio",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1988",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 2,
                     "uuid": "8fcee36c-411a-4fc8-8217-b9a07a34d3da",
                     "text": "Popol Vuh, Espanhol",
                     "page": "pp. 39",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2021",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 2,
                     "uuid": "74bdb72d-1770-4694-8f8e-71e680f1d49c",
                     "text": "Popol Vuh, English",
                     "page": "Ch. 3, pp. 8",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1954",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3c81aa4a-3030-4767-861a-25f13272776f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Sempre presente",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: Limits 1</b><br /><br />What if the <i>Popol Vuh</i> was not written literally, but symbolically—as an abstraction?<br ></br>Before this reflection, had the possibility that the texts might not be literal ever crossed your mind?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Abstraction and Facts\n\nIn the 19th century, according to the Gregorian calendar, Charles S. Peirce proposed that thought should not be considered exclusive to human beings. He even extended this idea to crystals (<htcite0>).\n\nAstronomical measurements made with telescopes show that the universe is expanding (<htcite1>), which indicates that in the past it was contracted—as explained in Chapter 4 of the *Literature* section and also in the *Atlas* of *History Tracers* (<htcite2>; <htcite3>). These data suggest that there is a connection among all elements present in nature.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f2efe0a4-6e8b-4ec1-8c7e-ebfd28ffa67f",
                     "text": "Santaella, Lucia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1af85131-52aa-49ee-8f9b-2409eb806900",
                     "text": "Hubble, Edwin",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1929",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2806b294-0d2a-4ca2-8008-b2b82791427a",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Undestandig Texts",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "12",
                        "day": "22"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f140d8d6-80cc-4d82-b9f7-c3ba06bf2ed3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Atlas",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/ESA/Planck_history_of_Universe.jpg\" id=\"imgESA2\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgESA2', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 2</b>: Planck history of Universe. ©ESA – C. Carreau (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('a1a7c478-9061-4160-ba43-301c081733e9'); return false;\"><i>ESA</i></a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Context\n\nDifferent Mesoamerican peoples used grinding stones (Figure 3) to prepare their food—that is, the stone was directly connected to their daily life. Likewise, stones also played an important role in the lives of various ancient cultures (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "56169de2-3737-4ca2-a857-ffc29bf9fb35",
                     "text": "Garcia Castro, Juan Antonio",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1988",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"metate3\" src=\"images/Teotihuacan/MetateTeotihuacan.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('metate3', '0%')\" /><b>Figure 3</b>: Metate from Mexico. Photo taken on <htdate0>, during a visit to the Achaeological Site of Teotihuacan, México.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "19"
                  }
